docs.abstract: It sometimes seems that automated bots are taking over social media and driving human discourse. But some (real) researchers aren’t so sure.
docs.snippet: It sometimes seems that automated bots are taking over social media and driving human discourse. But some (real) researchers aren’t so sure.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the long Memorial Day weekend, a Twitter storm blew in about bots, those little automatic programs that talk to us in the digital dimension as if they were human.

headline.print_headline: Was That a Bot Post? Maybe, Maybe Not

docs.abstract: Social activism and the pandemic dominated 2020, and the sports world responded in kind.
docs.snippet: Social activism and the pandemic dominated 2020, and the sports world responded in kind.
docs.lead_paragraph: In early May the ascendant tennis star Naomi Osaka declared on Twitter, “I’m done being shy.” Weeks later, after speaking out against police brutality following the killing of George Floyd, she addressed critics on social media who were suggesting in no uncertain terms that she stick to sports.

headline.main: A Year When Even Sports Wasn’t an Escape
headline.print_headline: In 2020, even sports offered no escape

docs.abstract: Elon Musk has tweeted about political topics regularly since taking over Twitter, often belittling some liberal causes. But what he stands for remains largely unclear.
docs.snippet: Elon Musk has tweeted about political topics regularly since taking over Twitter, often belittling some liberal causes. But what he stands for remains largely unclear.
docs.lead_paragraph: He has called himself an independent and a centrist, yet “economically right of center, maybe.” He has said he was until recently a supporter of only Democrats and voted for President Biden. He’s encouraged people to vote Republican, which he said he did for the first time this year. Last year, he once even declared himself indifferent about politics, saying he’d rather stay out of it altogether.

headline.main: Critics Say Musk Has Revealed Himself as a Conservative. It’s Not So Simple.
headline.print_headline: What Musk Stands For Is Not Clear

docs.abstract: With people stuck at home and so many other activities shut down, a lot of reading — or at least a lot of book buying — happened this year.
docs.snippet: With people stuck at home and so many other activities shut down, a lot of reading — or at least a lot of book buying — happened this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Like everybody else, book publishers will be happy to see the end of 2020. But for many of them, the year has brought some positive news, which has been as welcome as it was surprising: Business has been good.

headline.main: Surprise Ending for Publishers: In 2020, Business Was Good
headline.print_headline: It Was a Good Year for One Industry: Books

docs.abstract: Camae Ayewa makes a blend of hip-hop, spoken-word poetry, punk and electro as Moor Mother. In Irreversible Entanglements, she records scalding free jazz. Both have new albums this fall.
docs.snippet: Camae Ayewa makes a blend of hip-hop, spoken-word poetry, punk and electro as Moor Mother. In Irreversible Entanglements, she records scalding free jazz. Both have new albums this fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: The poet and musician Camae Ayewa is a study in nonstop movement. On a recent video call from Los Angeles, she chatted while pacing her apartment, stopping to open a few cabinets and pop a Ricola cough drop. “When people hang out with me, we’re not going to be just sitting down and talking the whole time,” she said. “I like creating. It’s my energy.”

headline.main: Moor Mother’s Musical Galaxy Grows Even Bigger
headline.print_headline: Her Musical Galaxy  Grows Even Bigger

docs.abstract: Newly restored, “Sisters,” by Brian De Palma, remade Alfred Hitchcock’s “Psycho” as a thriller for the disillusioned 1970s.
docs.snippet: Newly restored, “Sisters,” by Brian De Palma, remade Alfred Hitchcock’s “Psycho” as a thriller for the disillusioned 1970s.
docs.lead_paragraph: The 1973 slasher film “Sisters,” digitally restored and playing at the Quad Cinema, as well as streaming on services like FilmStruck, was Brian De Palma’s first homage to Alfred Hitchcock. Shamelessly lurid, it’s also his best.

headline.main: ‘Sisters’ Isn’t ‘Psycho,’ but It’s a Lacerating Spin on Hitchcock
headline.print_headline: De Palma’s Lacerating Spin on Hitchcock

docs.abstract: We chose the gesture purposefully. Our bodies were like flags flown at half-mast to mark a tragedy.
docs.snippet: We chose the gesture purposefully. Our bodies were like flags flown at half-mast to mark a tragedy.
docs.lead_paragraph: In early 2016, I began paying attention to reports about the incredible number of unarmed black people being killed by the police. The posts on social media deeply disturbed me, but one in particular brought me to tears: the killing of Alton Sterling in my hometown Baton Rouge, La. This could have happened to any of my family members who still live in the area. I felt furious, hurt and hopeless. I wanted to do something, but didn’t know what or how to do it. All I knew for sure is that I wanted it to be as respectful as possible.

headline.main: Eric Reid: Why Colin Kaepernick and I Decided to Take a Knee

docs.abstract: Critics acknowledge the success the New Museum in New York has achieved. But they say it has come at the expense of many people who work there.
docs.snippet: Critics acknowledge the success the New Museum in New York has achieved. But they say it has come at the expense of many people who work there.
docs.lead_paragraph: Considered one of the finest small museums in America, the New Museum is routinely acclaimed for its exhibitions of contemporary art under the stewardship of its longtime director, Lisa Phillips.

headline.main: The New Museum Is World Class, but Many Find It a Tough Place to Work
headline.print_headline: On Its Ascent,  New Museum Exacts a Toll

docs.abstract: The Redskins receiver made an obscene gesture to fans after Monday night’s game, which he said was motivated by racial slurs from the crowd.
docs.snippet: The Redskins receiver made an obscene gesture to fans after Monday night’s game, which he said was motivated by racial slurs from the crowd.
docs.lead_paragraph: Washington Redskins receiver Terrelle Pryor said he was called racial slurs from the crowd during Monday night’s game at Kansas City, and the N.F.L. said on Thursday that it was looking into the incident.

headline.main: Terrelle Pryor Says He Was Racially Taunted; N.F.L. to Investigate

docs.abstract: An African-American studies professor suggests ways to mark the month, from David Driskell’s paintings and Dance Theater of Harlem’s streamed performances to the rollicking return of “Queen Sugar.”
docs.snippet: An African-American studies professor suggests ways to mark the month, from David Driskell’s paintings and Dance Theater of Harlem’s streamed performances to the rollicking return of “Queen Sugar.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Black History Month feels more urgent this year. Its roots go back to 1926, when the historian Carter G. Woodson developed Negro History Week, near the February birthdays of both President Abraham Lincoln and the abolitionist Frederick Douglass, in the belief that new stories of Black life could counter old racist stereotypes. Now in this age of racial reckoning and social distancing, our need to connect with each other has never been greater.

headline.main: Black History Month Is a Good Excuse for Delving Into Our Art
headline.print_headline: Delving Into Art for Black History Month
